</table><para id="fs-id1170572236179"><emphasis effect="italics">Note</emphasis>: The values in this table were obtained using a calculator and using all the places given in the calculator output.</para><para id="fs-id1170572558630">As we read down each <m:math><m:mrow><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mtext>sin</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.1em"/><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math> column, we see that the values in each column appear to be approaching one. Thus, it is fairly reasonable to conclude that <m:math><m:mrow><m:munder><m:mrow><m:mtext>lim</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">→</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:munder><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mtext>sin</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.1em"/><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mfrac><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo>.</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math> A calculator or computer-generated graph of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mi>f</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mi>x</m:mi><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mo>=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:mrow><m:mtext>sin</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.1em"/><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mi>x</m:mi></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:math> would be similar to that shown in <link target-id="CNX_Calc_Figure_02_02_003"/>, and it confirms our estimate.</para>
